		<div class="entry-content"><div class="w592"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="associatedMedia" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/07/18/opinion/nyto-writer/nyto-writer-tmagArticle.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/07/18/opinion/nyto-writer/nyto-writer-tmagArticle.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/07/18/opinion/nyto-writer/nyto-writer-tmagArticle.jpg" id="100000003009282" width="592" height="586" alt=""   /><meta itemprop="height" content="586"><meta itemprop="width" content="592"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text"></span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> Piotr Redlinski for The New York Times</span></figcaption></figure></div>
<div id="sharetools-story" class="sharetools theme-classic sharetools-story" data-shares="email|Email,facebook|Share,twitter|Tweet,save|Save,show-all|More,ad" data-url="//op-talk.blogs.nytimes.com/2014/07/21/why-writers-are-opening-up-about-money-or-the-lack-thereof/" data-title="Why Writers Are Opening Up About Money (or the Lack Thereof)" data-description="A new wave of writing about money has opened up broader conversations about who can afford to enter the publishing world today.">
				<div class="ad sharetools-inline-article-ad"></div>
				<div id="MiddleLeft" class="ad middle-left-ad nocontent robots-nocontent"></div>
				</div><p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Writers may always have worried about money, but now seems a particularly fertile time for writing about it.Â <a href="//scratchmag.net/">Scratch Magazine</a>, launched last year, takes as its purview âWriting + money + life.â <a href="//thebillfold.com/">The Billfold</a> routinely runs stories on how <a href="//thebillfold.com/slug/the-art-of-freelance-writing/">freelance writers</a> and other <a href="//thebillfold.com/2014/03/talking-to-the-doubleclicks-about-running-a-band-and-a-business/">creative types</a> âdo money.â The novelist Emily Gould opened up about her financial life in a popular Medium <a href="https://medium.com/@emilygould/how-much-my-novel-cost-me-35d7c8aec846">essay</a> and subsequent <a href="//electricliterature.com/interview-emily-gould-author-of-friendship-and-founder-of-emily-books/">interviews</a>, and The Guardianâs Alison Flood recently <a href="//www.theguardian.com/books/2014/jul/08/authors-incomes-collapse-alcs-survey?CMP=twt_gu">reported</a> on the sorry state of writersâ incomes (which, in turn, inspired some <a href="https://www.twitter.com/michelledean/status/486495019998535682">critique</a> from Gawkerâs Michelle Dean).</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">This spate of talk about writing and money has opened up broader conversations about who can afford to enter the profession today, and who gets shut out.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Manjula Martin, the cofounder of Scratch, told Op-Talk that âthere has always been this tension for writers around how to make a living and how to make art.â However, she said, growing job insecurity in writing professions and beyond may have led to a new wave of anxiety: âAs the economy is changing and as things just feel more precarious in our culture, that bleeds through to the literary culture. And I think a big part of that too is a question of, âis literature and are the arts going to continue to be valued in ways that we have perhaps always just assumed they would be?ââ</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Cord Jefferson, a TV writer and journalist who has written about money at <a href="//scratchmag.net/article/52749a72c873d951eb2ec910/the_boy_with_the_least_toys">Scratch</a> and <a href="//gawker.com/5989280/when-people-write-for-free-who-pays">elsewhere</a>, also sees an increase in articles about money asÂ âa symptom of a broader change in culture.â He told Op-Talk: âEveryoneâs talking a lot more about money. The financial crisis really rocked a lot of people to their core, and I think people considering these kinds of issues is a broad societal thing more so than it is just a writerly thing.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Changes in the way writing jobs work may play a role, too. Ms. Martin mentioned a rise in the âgig economyâ as part of a mix of factors that might make writing as a profession feel more uncertain. Meanwhile, Nicole Dieker, a freelancer who writes a <a href="//thebillfold.com/slug/the-art-of-freelance-writing/">series</a> for The Billfold on freelancing and finances, told Op-Talk thatÂ âmore and more people are turning to freelancing,â whether itâs because they prefer not to work traditional jobs or because they arenât able to get them. And she cited a <a href="//www.nytimes.com/interactive/2014/06/05/upshot/how-the-recession-reshaped-the-economy-in-255-charts.html">recent chart</a> at The Upshot showing that jobs in âInternet publishing, broadcasting and searchâ have actually proliferated since the recession. âInternet writing is skyrocketing,â she said. âThere are all kinds of new magazines, there are all kinds of new content sites, there are all of these jobs for writers that didnât exist even three years ago.â This proliferation has people talking, both about making a career in freelancing and about how much they can really expect to make from this kind of career.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">That answer may be not be as much as some might hope, at least at the outset. Ms. Dieker, who also posts her monthly freelance income on <a href="//hello-the-future.tumblr.com/">her Tumblr</a>, says that sheâs hoping to make $40,000 gross this year, but that other freelancers routinely ask her how she manages to make that much when theyâre bringing in much less. She also notes that sheâs making a lot more than when she started out: âLike any other career, you grow it.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">For some writers, though, the current financial climate can make it feel like their careers are shrinking. Erin Hosier, an agent at Dunow, Carlson &amp; Lerner who is working on a <a href="//www.themillions.com/2014/05/dont-ever-do-it-for-the-money-a-conversation-with-my-agent.html">memoir</a>,Â told Op-Talk in an email that writers might be opening up about money right now because book advances were stagnating. âIn as much as it has always been difficult for writers to make a living,â she said, âitâs definitely worse now,â as pay for writers has stalled or fallen while the cost of living has risen.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Eleanor Jackson, also an agent at Dunow, Carlson &amp; Lerner, told Op-Talk in an email, âI wouldnât say it is harder to make a living writing now than it once was, because I think the financial landscape for writers has always been really difficult, but I do believe it is particularly unpredictable right now. Advances for books can range from four figures to seven figures, editors are constantly being hired and fired, publishers are merging and imprints are being eliminated and created on a regular basis.â All this, combined with the big changes the book industry faces as e-books rise in prominence, âmakes career planning difficult. Whereas an author could once hope to work with a single editor and publisher throughout their entire career, that kind of continuity is now virtually impossible.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">This isnât to say that no writers can make it work. The novelist and memoirist Brando Skyhorse told Op-Talk in an email, âI made two medium-size five-figure advances last me five years,â in part by being frugal: âLiving alone was, in essence, the only luxury I sprung for. That, and a new bed.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">However, he noted that the cost of entering the publishing industry affects who becomes an editor, and thus whom those editors publish. He cited the Radcliffe Publishing Course, <a href="//www.columbia.edu/cu/record/archives/vol26/vol26_iss4/2604_Radcliffe_Course.html">now</a> the Columbia Publishing Course, a prestigious training program that costs <a href="//www.journalism.columbia.edu/page/236-frequently-asked-questions/237">nearly $8,000</a>: âCertain kinds of fiction on submission will automatically generate more attention, be read more empathetically, and upon publication be reviewed far more extensively, than other kinds of books because the gatekeepers, be they from Radcliffe or elsewhere, come from a more homogenous background and of course will be more interested in books that speak to their own experiences.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Mr. Jefferson identified a similar homogeneity at prestigious publications, whose mastheads he said were often dominated by âpeopleÂ whose backgrounds afforded them the opportunity to live in New York City and work for a pittance while they made their way up.â He added, âOur society loses a great many creatives who just canât afford to create.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">And for Ms. Martin, financial obstacles to writing and editing careers leave everyone worse off. âIf you canât afford to access the routes toward a publishing career,â she explained, ânot only does that industry suffer as a result of having less diversity, but your stories are not actually getting out there.â Readers arenât hearing from âthe kid who canât afford to do four simultaneous unpaid internships in New York City and has to just get a job, or the woman whoâs raising a kid and canât go do a residency for three weeks.â And, she said, âreaders are just like those people, and readers I think actually want those stories.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">At Scratch, sheâs hoping to shed a little light, at least, on the big questions of creative work and financial reality. âItâs still really scary and sometimes dangerous to talk about how much money you make,â she said, âand so weâre trying to bring a little honesty to that.â</p>
	</div>
